We recommended that management:

a.	Locate all the source documents and MOA/Trust Agreements with the source agencies to review the terms and conditions corresponding to the funds transferred in relation to the implementation of programs and projects;

b.	Determine if the specific programs or projects for which the funds were transferred were already implemented, goods/services were already delivered, liquidation of funds were already submitted and received by the source agencies, and liabilities were already settled for proper adjustments in the books;

c.	Return to the source agency or remit to the Bureau of Treasury any unused/unexpended balance if so stipulated in the MOA/Trust Agreement and furnish COA with copies of Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) taking up the return or remittance;

d.	Designate a focal person who would be responsible in monitoring the status of project implementation of funds transferred from source agencies, be it an NGA, a GOCC or an LGU; and



e.	Furnish COA with copies of the source documents of the funds previously transferred, the MOA/Trust Agreements with source agencies, and Office Order of the designated focal person, within 15 days from receipt hereof.

We recommended that the Municipality’s GFPS:
Conduct gender mainstreaming through gender audit and gender analysis of its policies, programs, services and the current situation of the LGU in terms of GAD compliance;
To equip the GFPS with the in-depth knowledge and capacity on GAD, thru trainings and seminars such as those relating to gender-responsive planning and budgeting, gender analysis, gender audit and the use of various GAD tools for the LGU’s GAD implementation of PAPs;
Institutionalize the GAD database with adequate and systematically gathered age- and sex-disaggregated data which will provide the bases for gender analysis, planning, programming and policy formulation; and
Revisit and strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 9710 and other related provisions of law.

To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the LCE institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
to conduct risk assessment;
to identify critical processes and functions;
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.
We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

32.6	We recommended that management:

a) 	Demand from the contractor the immediate completion of the construction of the four projects; 

b) 	Refrain from approving extension of project completion without concrete and valid reason; 

c) 	Direct the MEO to make overall considerations in the planning phase of the projects; and

d) 	Require the contractor to pay liquidated damages. If the contractor has not been paid the remaining contract price, deduct the liquidated damages from such amount.

Recommendation:
We recommended that management:
Locate all the source documents and MOA/Trust Agreements with the source agencies to review the terms and conditions corresponding to the funds transferred in relation to the implementation of programs and projects;
Determine if the specific programs or projects for which the funds were transferred were already implemented, goods/services were already delivered, liquidation of funds were already submitted and received by the source agencies, and liabilities were already settled for proper adjustments in the books;
Return to the source agency or remit to the Bureau of Treasury any unused/unexpended balance if so stipulated in the MOA/Trust Agreement and furnish COA with copies of Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) taking up the return or remittance;
Designate a focal person who would be responsible in monitoring the status of project implementation of funds transferred from source agencies, be it an NGA, a GOCC or an LGU; and
Furnish COA with copies of the source documents of the funds previously transferred, the MOA/Trust Agreements with source agencies, and Office Order of the designated focal person, within 15 days from receipt hereof.
Management’s Comment:
Management commented that they have difficulty in locating the necessary documents relative to the projects due to lack of proper turn-over from previous employees who were in charged. Nevertheless, they assured to exert best efforts to comply with the recommendations.

We recommended that management require the Municipal Accountant to:

Ensure the completeness of prescribed supporting documents for the granting of cash advances in processing claims for payment thereof; 

Stop processing cash advances of elected officials other than for official travel; 


Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances; and

Measures to enforce immediate liquidation of outstanding cash advances be enacted such as sending demand letter to accountable officer when the AO failed to liquidate/ effect deduction from the salaries/ benefits due to the concerned employee.

We recommended that:

The LCE prioritize the conduct of physical inventory of all the Municipality’s properties by the Inventory Committee and cause the submission of an updated and complete RPCPPE duly reconciled with accounting and property records to properly establish the existence, ownership and valuation of the PPEs and ensure its fair presentation in the FS;
For the Accounting Office and CGSO to observe proper recording of transactions relating to supplies and property of the Municipality Government, maintain their respective records which contains complete data/information, which in turn will support the PPE accounts as appearing in the FS;
The Municipality Government and the DepEd Municipality Schools Division Office establish an internal control policy or agreement for the effective property management and accountability of all PPE charged against SEF to establish the actual existence and condition of the property accountabilities purportedly issued to DepEd officers (and for all the other offices of the Municipality Government, for this matter) and as such ensure that:
accountability over issued property items is established at any point in time;
the Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment (ARE)s are prepared and updated regulary or whenever there is a change of accountability over the item; and
the existence and condition of the PPE items are reasonably determined every year.

d) Copies of the JEVs taking up the reclassification/adjustments should be separately submitted to COA for verification.

